### Surviving aircraft

Despite its relatively high production numbers and crucial role, the challenging nature and specialized design of the AT-9 meant few survived the post-war culling. Those that remain are testaments to dedicated preservation efforts.

*   **41-12150** – An AT-9 that is currently on static display at the venerable [National Museum of the United States Air Force](/National_Museum_of_the_United_States_Air_Force) in [Dayton, Ohio](/Dayton,_Ohio). Its journey to display was not a simple one, requiring extensive restoration. The museum staff embarked on a painstaking process, meticulously incorporating components from two incomplete airframes to create a single, coherent example. Furthermore, numerous parts had to be fabricated from scratch on-site, a testament to the rarity of original components and the dedication required to bring this difficult trainer back to a display-worthy condition. [3]
*   **42-56882** – Another AT-9, this one held in storage at the [Pima Air & Space Museum](/Pima_Air_%26_Space_Museum) in [Tucson, Arizona](/Tucson,_Arizona). [4] This particular aircraft was recovered from a crash site in 1993, a recovery effort that likely involved considerable logistical challenges given the remote or difficult locations such crash sites often entail. Following its recovery, it was transferred to the museum for what was anticipated to be a comprehensive restoration. [5] [6] [7] However, as of current reports, the aircraft remains incomplete, presenting a formidable and extensive restoration project for the museum, highlighting the significant resources and time required to return such a rare and complex artifact to its former glory for public display. [ [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) ]

