### General characteristics

*   **Crew:** 2 (a pilot and an instructor, both presumably with nerves of steel)
*   **Length:** 31&#160;ft 8&#160;in (9.65&#160;m) — a relatively compact airframe for a twin-engine machine, contributing to its "lively" handling.
*   **Wingspan:** 40&#160;ft 4&#160;in (12.29&#160;m)
*   **Height:** 9&#160;ft 10&#160;in (3.00&#160;m)
*   **Wing area:** 233&#160;sq&#160;ft (21.6&#160;m<sup>2</sup>)
*   **[Airfoil](/Airfoil):** root: [NACA 23015.9](/NACA_airfoil); tip: [NACA 4410](/NACA_airfoil) [9] — specific aerodynamic profiles chosen to achieve its intended, less-than-stable flight characteristics.
*   **Empty weight:** 4,494&#160;lb (2,038&#160;kg)
*   **Gross weight:** 6,060&#160;lb (2,749&#160;kg)
*   **Powerplant:** 2 &#xD7; [Lycoming R-680-9](/Lycoming_R-680-9) radial engines, each producing 295&#160;hp (220&#160;kW) — sufficient power to ensure it wasn't just difficult, but also capable of simulating the speeds of more powerful combat aircraft.
*   **Propellers:** 2-bladed propellers

### Performance

*   **Maximum speed:** 197&#160;mph (317&#160;km/h, 171&#160;kn) — a respectable speed for a trainer, allowing for realistic engagement in simulated combat scenarios.
*   **Cruise speed:** 175&#160;mph (282&#160;km/h, 152&#160;kn)
*   **Range:** 750&#160;mi (1,210&#160;km, 650&#160;nmi)
*   **Service ceiling:** 19,000&#160;ft (5,800&#160;m) — high enough to introduce pilots to the challenges of operating at altitude, including thinner air and colder temperatures, without requiring supplemental oxygen systems typically found in combat aircraft at higher altitudes.
*   **Time to altitude:** 10,000&#160;ft (3,000&#160;m) in 8 minutes 36 seconds — demonstrating a reasonable climb rate for its intended training role.

